---
// Colophon — how the site is built (stack, design, principles, build note).
// Static page — prerender to HTML served from the CDN (output: 'server' is on-demand by default).
export const prerender = true;
import { css } from 'styled-system/css';
import { tag } from 'styled-system/recipes';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import { prosePara, proseH2, proseLink } from '../styles/prose';

const para = prosePara;
const h2 = proseH2;
const link = proseLink;
const term = css({ color: 'text', fontWeight: 600 });

// The stack, as a small bordered record — same row-list idiom as the condensed
// experience block on /about/, so it reads as "materials used" rather than a
// bulleted feature dump.
const stackCard = css({ listStyle: 'none', m: 0, p: '0.25rem 1.25rem', bg: 'bgCard', border: '1px solid token(colors.border)', borderRadius: 'lg' });
const stackRowBase = css({ display: 'flex', flexDirection: 'column', gap: '0.3rem', py: '0.85rem' });
const stackRowDivider = css({ borderTop: '1px solid token(colors.border)' });
const stackHead = css({ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', alignItems: 'baseline', justifyContent: 'space-between', gap: '0.2rem 1rem' });
const stackName = css({ color: 'text', fontWeight: 600 });
const stackNote = css({ color: 'textMuted', fontSize: '0.9rem', lineHeight: 1.7 });

const STACK = [
  { name: 'Astro', url: 'https://astro.build', role: 'Framework', note: 'Every page is prerendered to static HTML.' },
  { name: 'Panda CSS', url: 'https://panda-css.com', role: 'Styling', note: 'Zero-runtime, generated at build time.' },
  { name: 'MDX', url: 'https://mdxjs.com', role: 'Content', note: 'How the posts and labs get written.' },
  { name: 'Shiki', url: 'https://shiki.style', role: 'Code', note: 'Syntax highlighting, themed for light and dark.' },
  { name: 'Floating UI', url: 'https://floating-ui.com', role: 'Interactions', note: 'Powers the hover cards on terms, tools, and companies.' },
  { name: 'Satori', url: 'https://github.com/vercel/satori', role: 'Social cards', note: 'Renders the Open Graph images at build time.' },
  { name: 'Vercel', url: 'https://vercel.com', role: 'Hosting', note: 'The CDN, plus cookieless Web Analytics and Speed Insights.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colophon"
  description="How patricksaade.com is built — the stack, design choices, and principles behind the site."
>
  <PageHeader breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Colophon' }]} eyebrow="Colophon" title="How this site is built" description="What it's built with, and why it works the way it does." />

  <p class={para}>
    I designed this to be fast, readable, and private — static HTML with a little inline
    JavaScript, and nothing following you around. No cookies, no marketing trackers, and the
    analytics are cookieless (the full story is in the <a class={link} href="/privacy/">privacy
    policy</a>). It's semantic, keyboard-friendly, and it respects reduced motion.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>Why this exists</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    DFIR work means bouncing between a dozen disconnected tools — a hash calculator on one
    site, a timestamp converter on another, an event ID lookup buried in a PDF cheat sheet
    somewhere else. I wanted one place that actually has it all: reference material (the
    glossary, tool catalog, event ID lookup, and the ATT&amp;CK/D3FEND maps) sitting next to
    small tools that do real work (extract IOCs, decode timestamps, compute and identify
    hashes, build OSINT search-operator queries) — free, and the ones that process what you
    give them do it entirely client-side, so nothing you paste, type, or upload ever leaves
    your browser. That's also why the toolkit is reachable at{' '}
    <span class={term}>cyberkit.win</span>, independent of <span class={term}>patricksaade.com</span> —
    the tools stand on their own, whether or not you're here for the portfolio side of the site.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>What's actually here</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    There's more to this site than the posts, and it's built to be a working reference for
    analysts, not just a portfolio. A searchable <span class={term}>Glossary</span> covers 500+
    security concepts, with a new <span class={term}>Term of the Day</span> picked daily,
    alongside a free, open-source tools directory and a command cheat sheet for quick
    install/syntax lookup — each tool links to the glossary concept it implements, so looking up
    a term surfaces the tools that use it. Then there's a full MITRE ATT&amp;CK Coverage Map —
    the entire Enterprise matrix, generated straight from MITRE's own data, with a detail page for
    every technique — cross-linked to its defensive counterpart, a MITRE D3FEND map of
    countermeasures, so each technique shows what actually stops it, plus the tools that implement
    that defense. Look something up once, and the glossary, tools, and technique maps all point
    back to each other.
  </p>
  <p class={para}>
    ATT&amp;CK® and D3FEND™ are trademarks of The MITRE Corporation.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>A little craft</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    Small touches I like: ten palettes split evenly between dark and light, each held
    independently so switching modes never forgets your color pick; a field of drifting,
    connected nodes behind everything; and a hand-drawn cursor for anyone browsing with a mouse.
    Search lives on <span class={term}>⌘K</span>, sound is opt-in from the nav, and the whole
    thing installs like an app and stays readable offline. The site also has a DFIR sidebar — a
    compact icon rail docked to the left edge on every page, letting you jump straight to any
    reference page, framework map, or interactive tool without a trip back through the nav.
  </p>

  <h2 class={h2}>Built with</h2>
  <ul class={stackCard}>
    {
      STACK.map((s, i) => (
        <li class={`${stackRowBase} ${i === 0 ? '' : stackRowDivider}`}>
          <span class={stackHead}>
            <a class={`${link} ${stackName}`} href={s.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{s.name}</a>
            <span class={tag({ tone: 'muted' })}>{s.role}</span>
          </span>
          <span class={stackNote}>{s.note}</span>
        </li>
      ))
    }
    <li class={`${stackRowBase} ${stackRowDivider}`}>
      <span class={stackHead}>
        <a class={`${link} ${stackName}`} href="https://www.redaction.us" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Redaction</a>
        <span class={tag({ tone: 'muted' })}>Display type</span>
      </span>
      <span class={stackNote}>
        By Jeremy Mickel (<a class={link} href="https://www.mckltype.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MCKL</a>),
        drawn for Titus Kaphar &amp; Reginald Dwayne Betts' <em>The Redaction</em>. It comes in graded
        levels of erosion — I run the eroded grades on the wordmark, hero, and ticker. Used under
        the <a class={link} href="/fonts/redaction/OFL.txt">SIL Open Font License</a>.
      </span>
    </li>
    <li class={`${stackRowBase} ${stackRowDivider}`}>
      <span class={stackHead}>
        <a class={`${link} ${stackName}`} href="https://github.com/mozilla/Fira" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fira Mono</a>
        <span class={tag({ tone: 'muted' })}>Code type</span>
      </span>
      <span class={stackNote}>
        Mozilla's monospace, used under the <a class={link} href="/fonts/fira-mono/OFL.txt">SIL Open
        Font License</a>. The icons are <a class={link} href="https://lucide.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lucide</a>-style
        SVGs I draw by hand, so they follow the active palette.
      </span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class={h2}>The build</h2>
  <p class={para}>
    Straight up: I built the design and front-end with AI assistance
    (<a class={link} href="https://claude.com/claude-code" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claude Code</a>),
    then reviewed and refined every piece myself. The source is on
    <a class={link} href="https://github.com/patsaade/personal-portfolio" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>,
    and the footer links the exact build version and commit.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
